AGI -&nbsp; Healthier ready packages could reduce EU emissions by 48 million tonnes per year and save customers 2.8 billion euros (2.4 billion pounds) each year, as well as reduce disease. Fast food and ready meals provide more than a sixth of the EU's calories but contain much more salt and meat than doctors recommend, according to an analysis of the Systemiq consulting company commissioned by the non-profit environmental organizations Fern and Mother Brava. Scientists have found that imposing minimum health and sustainability standards for companies > which deal with selling most of these foods would bring enormous benefits to society.
&nbsp;
"Rendering the most healthy and sustainable ready meals is a policy without regret," said Eduardo Montero Mansilla, the Spanish Federation of Consumers and Users, one of the ten co-authored non-governmental organizations of the report.
&nbsp;
"We can improve the health of people and the planet at affordable prices," continued Montero Mansilla. The report examined the effects of the imposition of large food companies to respect the diets indicated by the World Health Organization, which aims to avoid malnutrition and non-transmissible diseases, and the EAT-Lancet Commission, which seeks to reduce environmental and human damage. In both cases, it has emerged that ready meals should contain on average about half of refined cereals and two-thirds less meat, as well as a significantly greater number of legumes.
&nbsp;
The report found that this would save consumers 2.8 billion euros in food and would reduce emissions of 48 million tonnes per year, but did not take into account the additional economic benefits resulting from the fact that hospitals would spend less money to treat patients and employers would lose less money due to workers' sickness days.
"We are experiencing a health crisis linked to food," said Alba Gil, of the European Public Health Alliance, co-author of the report.

